 bar\nitone of rare richness, personified\nin the Indian chieftain, said to be\nthe first of his race to have come\nto this pinnacle of vocal develop\n!81f iii US\nGOLQMB\nI1\nea\nTo Ratifv &25,0(XM00\nTreaty Develops\" Split\nAmong Republicans\nWASHINGTON. March 9 A spec\nial message sent by President Hard\ning to the senate today asking early\nratification of the $25,000,000 treaty\nwith Colombia started a vigorous\ncontroversy, with a considerable\ngroup of Republicans aligned in op\nposition. It was the president's first con\ngressional message and developed the\nfirst open differences between senate\niK-tniuiiiaus, communication\n1 inn Klw.n rr 1.\n\"as uiiki una was -uuuersiooa to nave\nrecommended ratification of the long\nvdelayed treaty principally on me\nground such action would improve re\nlations between the United States and\nColombia, and have a beneficial ef\nfect on relations between the United\nstates\nand Latin-America. Publica-!\ntion of the nj,essage, read in an ex'ec-i\nutive session, was deferred.\nObject To Immediate Action i\nImmediate action at the preaen? ex\ntra session was urged 'by Senator\nLodge, Republican leader, put objec\ntions came from both Republicans\nand Democrats, and the matcer went\nover until tomorrow, together with a\nproposal to discuss the treaty in open\nsession.\nPostponement of the treaty's con\nsideration until the April session ap\npeared probable. Leaders started' ne\ngotiations and tomorrow it wa hoped\nan agreement might be reached which\nwould defer consideration until next\nmonth, limit debate and fix a date for\na final vote. If the treaty is set aside\nuntil the April session, leaders To\nnight saidi that the extra senate ses\nsion might terminate Saturday. Should\n,tTONTINi:KI OV PAGE THREE)\nStudents Bar Half\nHose, Short Skirts,\nLove Making, Booze\nBREMERTON. Wash., March 9.\nEar puffs, half hose, short skirts,\nwhisky, love making and attending\npublic dances are denounced Vby\nstudents at the Union high school\nhere in resolutions adopted at\nmeetings today.\nThe girls set the fashions and\nthe boys took charge of morals.\nAs an aid to enforcement of the\nban on love making the students\nruled against the pairing of boys\nand girls in the double seats of the\nclass rooms.\nTO C\nPROLONG\ning the present term of the legisla-.\nture. On motion of Senator C M\nStoddard, of' Maricopa, and over the\nv.i ui otuKioi r. Willis, oi -o-,\nch se.t'no senate adopted a resolution\nproviding- that \"the senate of the\nfifth regular session oi the lsusla-\nCT\nIGUR IN HOUSE WNDINTS\nmiip oi-the state oi Anona shall con- Mil. was adopted in the senate today; ship for the French republic and of\ntinue in session until senate and by akvote of 11 to 5. Before adoption my Very genuine wish for the con\nhouse bills now pending before efth- the measure wa amended to include tinued promotion of its welfare and\ner the senate or house of represen- indirectly Globe, in Gila county. This' the further strengthening ir pos::iie.\ntatives s.iall haw bten acted upon.\" i was accomplished by removing an of the ties by which the two coun\nThe resolution w.ns adopted by a amendment limiting the distance I tries are bound in historic and fra\nstrict party vote, 10 to 7. The Deni-. which a county seat might be moved. 1 tvrnal friendship.\"\nNew Ruling Opens Way To Sale\nOf Beer And Wines As Medicine\nOr For Other Non-Beverage Use\nt\nPlaces These Alcoholic Liquors In Same Class With\nWhisky; Starts ftumor That J Mans To Obtain\nFurther. Restrictions' Are Wrecked\nWASHINGTON. March 9. Beer\nand wines are, given the same status\nas whisky under an opinion by the\nattorney general, made public today\noy iue Dureau oi internal revenue.\nThe ruling, one of the -most import\nant since the advent of prohibition,\nmakes, it possible for alcoholic liq\nuors to be used for medical and oth-ernon-bever:rge\npui poses, and for all\nto be manufactured and sold for\nthese purpose:; subject only, to limit\nations of the Volstead act on non\nbeverage intoricants.\nThe opinion was wTitten by for\nmer Attorney .General Palmer, and\nwas in reply to questions from inter\nnal revenue and prohibition officials\nbearing on construction of half a doz\nen moot points in the law.\nMay Upset Regulations\nWhether it will upset any regula\ntions of the revenue and enforcement\nbureaus had not been made known\ntonight. Commissioner Williams say\ning he had not an opportunity to\nstudy the- opinion. He said officials\nconcerned with enforcement would\nprepare at once to draft regulations.\nThere were many rumors that the\nopinion had wrecked plans of dry ad\nvocates to obtain further restrictions\nof liquor sales. Officials refused to\ncomment, on the reports, however,\nbut Wayne B. Wheeler.- general coun\nsel for the Anti-Saloon League, in a\nstatement said 39 states had state\ncodes prohibiting the prescribing -oti\nbeer for medical purposes. He de-'\nclared that the opinion was not in\naccord with the federal law.\n\"Congress clearly did not Intend to\nattempt o legalize what the state\nlaws prohibit,\" he said. \"Unless the\nopinion is overruled, congress .should\nr Wend the\nlaw. It was difficult to\noverrule it because the government\nr.nd- the brewers are on the same side\nTjd there is no one to contest it, un-'\nBY RED UPRISING\nPetrograd Situation Vague\nDespite Report That Reb\nels Have Seized Citv-\nBATUM, March 9. a Bolshevik\nuprising has broken out here. Thou\nsands of persons, in addition to the\nallied mission and members of the\nGeorgian government, -are leaving.\nNo Authoritative News\nLONDON. March 9.- Information\ngiven in the house of .commons to\nday from British representatives in\nthe Baltic states appeared to show-\nBAM MENACED TOREIGN\nmat tne government is without au- rents voiced a renewed pledge of Pan\nthoritative news from Russia. It was American solidarity. The message re\nannounced that the situation at Mos- Iorted in press dispatches as having\ncow and Petrograd was obscure, but 'een sent by King George of Greut\nit was believed righting was proceed- Britain, and the president's reply,\ning in Petrograd; that Kronstadt whs were omitted from the list given out.\nin the power of the revolutionary, Many Send Felicitations\nleader Koslosky and that the attt-i In addition to President\ntude of the Red army is uncertain.\nBut all reports were conflicting. It\nwas assumed that the fact that Trot\nrky had been given dictatorial pow\ners and chief command showed that\nthe soviet government regarded the\nposition serious.\nRed Army Retreats\nA Wednesday dispatch to the\nTimes from Riga says Bolshevik lead\ners in Petrograd escaped by motor\ncar following the capture by the rev\nolutionaries today of the city with\nthe exception of the Nicolal and Fin-\nCONTINUED ON PAGE FOVK)\nADOPTS COUNT? SEAT\nTHIS SESSION\nocratic senators were absent.\nBo,h h\"8e night sessions\nB,fhnt Durin the day and niSnt\nsession many measures were con-\nfidered but fewf theui\nmuch popular Interest.\nwere of\nSenate -bill No. 141, known as the\nanti Tombstone county seat removal\nless the new attorney general over\nrules the opinion.'\nOpinion Somewhat Ambiauous\nThe opinion appeared ambiguous\nin some respects, ofririals said, and\nas a reeult they could not determine\nwhether, the government had power\nto limit prescriptions a physician\nmay write except that the law speci\nfies no more, than a pint per pcrsoit\nin 10 clays. Palmer declared he be\nlieved it the purpose of congress to\nleave the physicians \"unfettered by\ngovernmental control\" yet he thought\nregulations might properly restrict\nthe amount sold on a prescription.\nPalmer called attention to provis\nions of law which apparently had left\nthe physician to act on his judgment.\nHe suggested then that when a phy\nsician abused the privilege he could\nbe dealt with criminally, but added\nthat in no case should the judgment\nof the physician be supplanted by\nthat of enforcement officials.\nCan't Withhold Permits\nReplying to the question whether\nthe government could restrict per\nmits to manufacture, sell or pre\nscribe. Palmer explained that\" the\nVolstead act had limited only classes\nto which permits could be. issued and\nhad permitted no discrimination, be\ntween persons within those classes.\nHe said the withholding of permits\ncould not be done- legally, even\nthough officials were convinced few-\ni er permits would suffice in any given\nI state or c ltv\"\nPalmer advised\nofficials that thev\nhad \"ample authority\" to write such\nregulations as thev beiieved neces\nsary to make certain enforcement of1\nthe law. Dry advocates stressed this\nstatement! declaring that by it means\nwould be found which would circum\nvent and handicap the sale of beer\nanj wines and would pot throw open\nthe door to manufacture is quanti\nanti-prohibitionists insisted\nties or iuru aiconouc Deer again as\nGREET HARDING\nFrench President Voices\nGood Will; King George's\nMessage.\nNot Revealed\nWASHINGTON, March 9. Mes\nsages of felicitation exchanged by\nPresident Harding and foreign rulers,\nexpressing hopes for peace and friend\nship were made public today.\nA note of economic as well as poli\ntical cooperation was sounded in the\nexchange between Mr. Harding and\nPresident Millerand of France, while\nmost of the messages that passed with\nSouth and Central American tires!-\nniose wnose congratulatory expres\nsions were included in thejannounce\nment were Kiug Albert of Belgium,\nKing Victor Emmanue: or naiy. King\nGustaf of Sweden, King Boris of Bul\ngaria, Sultan Ahmed Ghadjar of Per\nsia. President Pessoa of Brazil. Pres\nident Melendez of Salvador. President\nGondra of Paraguay, President Acos\nta of Costa Rica, President Bustillos\nof Venezuela. President Suarez of\nColombia, President Porras of Pana\nma, President Brum of Uruguay.\nPresident Menocai or Cuba and Pres\nident Saavedra of Bolivia.\nAfter recalling the trials through\nwhich the United States had passed.\nPresident Millerand's message said:\n\"The solidarity of Fiance and the\nUnited States, which is so powerfully\ncontributed to their common victory,\nwill also prove their safeguard dur\ning peace. The political or economic\nweakening of either republic would\nmeau impairment of the other. Their\ninterest as well as their sentiment\nbids them to stand by each other, and\nthus we are sure will be perpetuated\nthe noble traditions which for nearlj\nh century and a half have associated\nour two great democracies ror me\ncommon good of mankind.\"\nPledges France Friendship\nMr. Harding replied:\n\"I thank you sincerely for the cor\ndiality of your appreciated telegram\nof congratulations and good wishes,\nand assure you of my abiding friend\nFRENCH ASSURE\nNO INTENTION\nOF PERMANENT\nOCCUPATION\nSupreme Council Decides\nOn 50 Per Cent Toll On,'\nSale Of German Goods\nDKLGJAXN SKJZK CITY\nPeople Of Occupied Zone\nHail Arrival Of Allied\nTroops With Relief\nAMERICAN MILITARY HEAD\nQUARTERS, COBLENZ, Marcrt\n9. (By the Associated Press) N\nThe inter allied Rhineland com\nmission has decreed a censor\nship over wire communications\nfor a period of eight days. The\ncensorship may be renewed in\ndefinitely. News of troop move\nments is being censored.\nLONDON. March (By the Asso\nciated Press) The penalties imposed\nupon Germany will cease only when\na satisfactory solution of the ouos\ntions of reparations, disarmament and\nwar criminals has been accepted by\nthe allies.\nThe supreme council so decided at\nits meeting tonight, at which M. Inl\nand declared that the French govern\nment had no intention of permanently\noccupying territory on the lert of tho\nRhine. He said that the only object\nwns to secure execution of the treaty.\nThe council agreed to instruct the\nallied high commission or the Rhine\nland to invite the attendant e of Ital\nian representatives when economic\nquestions resulting from the applica\ntion of the penalties were under con\nsideration. M. Briand and the heads of the\nother delegations expressed apprecia\ntion of Lloyd George's conduct or tli\"\nconference.\n50 Per Cent Sales Tax\nBesides dealing with sanctior the\ncouncil decided to dra a bi tor u\n50 per cent toll on the sales tr Ger\nman goods. It was stated that im\nports to the allied countries through\nneutral countries will be reauired to\nhave certificates from the respective\nchambers of common e In neutral\ncountries or in the countries of trans\nshipment showing origin of the goods.\nThe discussion of the questions re\nlating to Turkey and Greece was re\nsumed and tomorrow there will be\nprivate conversations with the Greeks\nand Turks. x\nPremier JJoyd George alluding to\nFrench nnwspapor comment on the\noccupation of additional German ter\nritory asked the French premier for\nassurances that annexation as-not\ncontemplated. Tho French comment\nindicated the belief that the institu\ntion of a customs barrier was likely\nto lead to a complete separation be\ntween the occupied territories and the\nrest of Germany.\nAsks Expression From Briand\nFormer Premier Clemenceau'a re\npudiation of permanent occupation\nwas brought up. Lloyd George said\nthat though he had oonnaenee in M.\nBriand and the good sense of the ma\njority of Frenchmen and although ho\nhad received assurances from former\nPremiers Clemenceau and Millerand.\nwho had fought hard against the an\nnexationist policy, he would welcome\na new and definite assurance from M.\nBriand that Franco contemplated\nneither annexation nor even autonomy\nor the Rhineland.\nM. Briand tlenied any such feeling\nexisted \"even In the back or the\nminds\" or responsible French states\nmen. Not five out or every hundred\nFrenchmen he asserted, dreamed or\niCO.VTINl'KD ON I'AGE 1 HUfciSt\nWorld Can't Go\nOn As It lias,\nSavs Marshall\nCLEVELAND, March 9. A plea\nfor the rejuvenation of Democratic\nideals in the American life by the\nleveling of class distinction In\nin America was made in an ad\ndress by former Vice President\nMarshall today.\n\"America is the hope or the\nworld,\" he said, \"and America\nrests upon the heart that is in the\nbreast of every American, man and\nwoman.\n\"The world e:nnot go on ns It\nhas. Disarmament must come\nsome day.\n\"Ict us live our democracy let\nus level all distinctions in class\nand make this America really\ndemocratic.\"","height":"29704","width":"24092"}}
